- Recognizes fewer than 4 out of the 5 letters chosen.

The child is at ‘Capital Letter Level’ if the child:
- Correctly recognizes at least 4 out of the 5 letters chosen.

If the child is at ‘Capital Letter Level’, then ask her to try to recognize small letters and then follow the instructions for small letter testing.

If she can recognize at least 4 out of 5 capital letters but cannot recognize small letters, then mark the child at ‘Capital Letter Level’.

If the child is not at ‘Capital Letter Level’ (cannot recognize at least 4 out of 5 letters chosen), then mark the child at ‘Beginner Level’.

## SMALL LETTERS

Ask the child to recognize any 5 small letters from the small letter list. Let the child choose the letters herself. If the child does not choose, point out any 5 letters to her.

- The child is not at ‘Small Letter Level’ if the child recognizes fewer than 4 out of the 5 letters chosen.

The child is at ‘Small Letter Level’ if the child:
- Correctly recognizes at least 4 out of the 5 letters chosen.

If the child is at ‘Small Letter Level’, then ask her to try to read words and then follow the instructions for word level testing.

If she can recognize at least 4 out of 5 small letters but cannot read words, then mark the child at ‘Small Letter Level’.

If the child is not at ‘Small Letter Level’ (cannot recognize at least 4 out of 5 letters chosen), then mark the child at ‘Capital Letter Level’.

## WORDS

Ask the child to read any 5 words from the word list. Let the child choose the words herself. If the child does not choose, point out any 5 words to her.

- The child is not at ‘Word Level’ if the child reads fewer than 4 out of the 5 words chosen.

The child is at ‘Word Level’ if the child:
- Reads at least 4 out of the 5 words correctly.

If the child is at ‘Word Level’, then ask her to try to read sentences and then follow the instructions for sentence level testing.

If she can correctly and comfortably read at least 4 out of 5 words but is still struggling with the sentences, then mark the child at ‘Word Level’.

If the child is not at ‘Word Level’ (cannot correctly read at least 4 out of the 5 words chosen), then mark the child at ‘Small Letter Level’.

## SENTENCES

Ask the child to read all 4 sentences.

- The child is not at ‘Sentence Level’ if the child reads fewer than 2 out of the 4 sentences correctly.

The child is at ‘Sentence Level’ if the child:
- Reads at least 2 out of the 4 sentences correctly.

If the child can read the sentences then mark the child at ‘Sentence Level’.

If the child is not at ‘Sentence Level’, then mark the child at ‘Word Level’.

---

**ON THE HOUSEHOLD SURVEY SHEET, MARK THE CHILD AT THE HIGHEST LEVEL SHE CAN REACH.**

---

**NOTE:**
The meaning section is only administered to children who are marked at Word or Sentence level in the English reading section.

For children marked at ‘Word Level’, ask the child to say the meaning of the words she has read correctly. The meaning of at least 4 words must be correct.

For children marked at ‘Sentence Level’, ask the child to say the meaning of the sentences she has read correctly. The meaning of at least 2 sentences must be correct.

The meaning can be given in the local language.